🧬 DNA + Blockchain (Realistic Version)

A “DNA blockchain” can only realistically mean:

cryptographic anchoring of genomic metadata,

consent tracking,

integrity verification,

auditability.


It does not mean:

storing a living genome in real time,

broadcasting DNA over RF,

or dynamically visualizing biology from the air.


A practical implementation would use:

SHA-256 hashes,

Merkle trees,

encrypted genomic references,

consent tokens,

decentralized audit logs.


The blockchain acts as:

proof of integrity,

timestamping,

authorization,

audit history.


Not as biological transmission.


